    <fr:title text="The principle of well-founded induction › "><fr:link href="jms-00NP.xml" title="The principle of well-founded induction" addr="jms-00NP" type="local">The principle of well-founded induction</fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:p>One direction is trivial: suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex> and thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=S]]></fr:tex>, and fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  x \implies  y \in  S]]></fr:tex> holds. To show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex> we use our assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>

 <html:p>In the other direction, we suppose that for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  x\implies  y\in  S]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>. We need to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>

 <html:p>Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex>, we need to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>. Suppose to the contrary that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\not \in  S]]></fr:tex>. Then the complement <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\setminus  S]]></fr:tex> is non-empty and therefore has a minimal element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>

 <html:p>We will deduce that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S]]></fr:tex>, which is contradictory. By assumption we have <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  m\implies  y\in  S)\implies  m\in  S\text {.}]]></fr:tex></html:p>

 <html:p>It therefore sufices to prove the antecedent:</html:p>
 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  m \implies  y\in  S
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <html:p>Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\prec  m]]></fr:tex>, we see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> cannot lie outside <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> because it is smaller than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> is the smallest element that lies outside <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>. Therefore, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S]]></fr:tex> which contradicts our assumption <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\not \in  S]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
