            <fr:title text="The principle of well-founded induction">The principle of well-founded induction</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prec \colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="jms-00NL.xml" title="Well-founded relation" addr="jms-00NL" type="local">well-founded relation</fr:link> and fix a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex> holds if and only if for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  x\implies  y\in  S]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>In other words, to show that every element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, it is enough to show that for any element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex>, the elements below <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> lie in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
